{"id":422,"date":"2010-05-03T10:23:59","date_gmt":"2010-05-03T15:23:59","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/?p=422"},"modified":"2010-05-03T10:23:59","modified_gmt":"2010-05-03T15:23:59","slug":"navi-language-code","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/2010\/05\/navi-language-code\/","title":{"rendered":"Na&#039;vi language code"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>Today, I needed to look up a language code for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Na%27vi_language\">Na&#8217;vi<\/a>, the language natively spoken on the fictional moon Pandora, created by Paul Frommer for the movie Avatar.\u00a0 When adding a new language to Mightyverse, we record the ISO codes and use them in the URL of a search and someday we&#8217;ll cross-link with amazing language resources like <a href=\"http:\/\/www.ethnologue.com\/\">Ethnologue<\/a>. Usually these codes are easy to find.\u00a0 Not today.<\/p>\n<p>I worry when the most authoritative reference I can find is wikipedia, which reports that the ISO 639-2 code is &#8216;art&#8217;.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone\" title=\"wikipedia\" src=\"http:\/\/img.skitch.com\/20100503-fg6wem6ysqwbet2a7pu82yg6sj.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"289\" height=\"154\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Language identification moves at infrequent intervals.\u00a0 It is not like being assigned a port number. I read further that the most recent <a href=\"http:\/\/www.sil.org\/iso639-3\/\">ISO 639-3<\/a> change request list was approved on January 20, 2010 and I didn&#8217;t see Na&#8217;vi there.\u00a0 It is likely queued up with the 2010 change requests.<\/p>\n<p>I read that ISO uses the prefix &#8216;art&#8217; for artificial languages.\u00a0 (The art code is on the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.loc.gov\/standards\/iso639-2\/php\/code_list.php\">639-2 list<\/a> and therefore also part of 639-3).\u00a0 So, the full RFC3066 (really RFC4646) code would be &#8216;art-nav&#8217;, which is also the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wiktionary.org\/wiki\/Wiktionary:Language_codes\">wiktionary<\/a> code.\u00a0 So, until we get the official word in January 2011 or whenever RFC4646 codes get ratified, here&#8217;s what I&#8217;m going with:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>ISO 639-1:\u00a0 n\/a<\/li>\n<li>ISO 639-2:\u00a0 art<\/li>\n<li>ISO 639-3:  art<\/li>\n<li>RFC3066\u00a0 :  art-nav<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Today, I needed to look up a language code for Na&#8217;vi, the language natively spoken on the fictional moon Pandora, created by Paul Frommer for the movie Avatar.\u00a0 When adding a new language to Mightyverse, we record the ISO codes and use them in the URL of a search and someday we&#8217;ll cross-link with amazing [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":84,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[1],"tags":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/422"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/84"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=422"}],"version-history":[{"count":0,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/422\/revisions"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=422"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=422"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=422"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}